[Patient] How much fluid should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for 1.5-2 liters of fluid per day, but follow your doctor's advice.
[Patient] Can I drink water, or should I stick to specific fluids?
[Healthcare Educator] Water is best, but limit caffeine and alcohol intake as they can worsen heart failure.
[Patient] How can I track my fluid intake throughout the day?
[Healthcare Educator] Use a measuring cup to monitor your fluid intake and keep a log.
[Patient] What if I feel thirsty all the time, should I drink more fluids?
[Healthcare Educator] It's important to balance fluid intake. Talk to your doctor if you feel constantly thirsty.
[Patient] Are there any foods I should avoid to manage my fluid intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit high-sodium foods like processed meats, canned soups, and salty snacks.
[Patient] Can I drink fruit juices or sports drinks as part of my fluid intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Stick to water as fruit juices and sports drinks can be high in sugar and sodium.
[Patient] Is it okay to have a little cheat treat like soda once in a while?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit sugary drinks like soda as they can contribute to fluid retention.
[Patient] How can I make sure I am not overhydrating or underhydrating?
[Healthcare Educator] Monitor your weight daily and report any sudden changes to your doctor.